{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"CONTAINER review (G4 — child consistency), parent c81c (plan-review fan-out optimization). Walked the 7 cross-child interaction modes for THIS child (S4, merge G3+G4 into one call per bin) WHOLE against the complete sibling roster (S1 0250, S2 c6e5, S3 ba7e, S5 1762, S6 da34) and the parent. ONE G4 FINDING (scope-overlap + conflicting-assumption: the per-child output guardrail S4 depends on is owned by the LATER sibling S5 and is absent from S4). Corroborates the prior container-review comment (ts 1782578778460634001).\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (modes CLEAN under ANTI-FP):\n- Implicit shared state: sizing.py container-cost projection (len(cont)*n_children*COST_AGENT, sizing.py:206/232) is touched by S3 (cost-model fix + container-never-shed), S4 (this child: 2N->N), S5 (<N after packing). Real shared state, but EXPLICITLY ordering-resolved by the parent Sequencing note (\"Land S3 -> S4 -> S5 STRICTLY in DAG order\") and the DAG S3->S4->S5. S4's remediation AC (\"sizing.py projection reflects N calls; shedding stays calibrated\") layers correctly on S3. No contradiction.\n- Dependency gap: NONE. S3 (ba7e) blocks 98c6; S6 (da34) blocks 98c6; S4 blocks S5 (1762) — matching parent DAG S1->{S2,S3}; S3->S4; S6->{S4,S5}; S4->S5. S4's remediation re-points the fidelity gate to the S6 semantic harness (DEPENDS ON S6), correctly declared.\n- Conflicting assumptions (cost/shedding): S4's \"halve container calls\" is consistent with S3's de-risk-D (halving pushes shed threshold past N=40; S3's \"never shed\" is the robust fix). S4 is positioned as a MITIGATION, not a competing fix. No conflict.\n- Ordering violation: NONE intrinsic — S4 is the middle node of the strict S3->S4->S5 chain; it takes the projection 2N->N, S5 then N->{<N}.\n- Consumer impact: S4 restructures the per-call criterion vocabulary (1->2) over the call structure S3 produces; S5 consumes S4's merged-call shape. Producer->consumer is DAG-ordered. The attribution remediation (validate criteria against {G3,G4}, drop out-of-set, preserve _container_child, mirror passes.py:222-224) correctly protects the coach/sidecar downstream consumers of the finding->criterion mapping. Consistent.\n- Residual references: S4's body still says \"Gate behind an OFFLINE EVAL\" while its own remediation supersedes this with \"Fidelity gate = the S6 semantic eval harness (DEPENDS ON S6), not a vague 'offline eval'.\" This is an intra-child stale label superseded in-ticket by its own remediation, with S6's own ticket carrying the matching semantic-harness contract — reads benignly under ANTI-FP. Recorded for editorial cleanup only, NOT a G4 finding.\n\nG4 FINDING:\n- finding: The \"REQUIRED structured per-child output guardrail\" is owned by sibling S5 (1762: \"Structured per-child sections in the prompt + REQUIRED per-child output so per-child attention isn't lost\") but is load-bearing for S4 and ABSENT from S4's spec. S4's own \"Why\" frames the merged call as \"per (child/bin)\" — i.e. it can batch >1 child — and S4 is the FIRST batching child in the strict S4->S5 chain. So the very batching tail-recall hazard the guardrail mitigates is present AT S4, yet S4's What/AC carry no per-child structured-output completeness requirement. The shared meta-evidence comment carried on S4/S5/S6 (ts 1782572460/463/466) states the batching recency/salience bias \"risks per-child DEPTH on tail children\" and that the guardrail \"(already in S5) is ESSENTIAL and must ALSO apply to S4,\" and that S6's eval \"should specifically check TAIL-child recall.\" Under strict DAG ordering, S4 lands WITHOUT the guardrail S5 owns — a scope/ownership split and a conflicting assumption (S4 assumes per-child fidelity is preserved; the mechanism that preserves it lives one step later).\n  criteria: [G4]\n  location: child 98c6 \"## What\" / \"## Acceptance Criteria\"; cross-ref sibling 1762 (S5) \"## What\" (REQUIRED per-child output) + shared meta-comment ts 1782572460471843001\n  evidence:\n    - \"S5 (1762) body: 'Structured per-child sections in the prompt + REQUIRED per-child output so per-child attention isn't lost' — the guardrail is scoped to S5 only.\"\n    - \"Shared meta-comment on S4/S5/S6: 'the REQUIRED structured per-child output guardrail (already in S5) is ESSENTIAL and must also apply to S4. S6's eval should specifically check TAIL-child recall.'\"\n    - \"S4 '## What' specifies the merged dual-rubric call + attribution but no per-child/bin structured-output completeness requirement; S4 '## Why' frames the call as 'per (child/bin)', so it can batch >1 child and the tail-recall hazard applies at S4.\"\n    - \"Mode = scope overlap + conflicting assumption: the guardrail's ownership sits in S5 while the dependency on it arises one step earlier in S4 (S4->S5), so under the parent's strict DAG ordering S4 lands WITHOUT it.\"\n  scenarios:\n    - \"S4 lands (S5 not yet started). A merged G3+G4 call over a >1-child bin attends mostly to the head child; the tail child gets a shallow pass. Aggregate G3/G4 finding counts match the separate-call baseline within tolerance, so S4's AC ('correctly attributed'; 'no accuracy regression within tolerance') and the S6 recall metric (if it does not check per-child/tail recall) both pass — but the tail child's child-coverage/consistency was effectively unreviewed; the parent fidelity AC is silently violated for the first batching child.\"\n  impact: \"S4 can satisfy its tolerance/attribution AC while regressing per-child (tail) review depth, because the per-child completeness guardrail that prevents this is scoped to the LATER sibling S5. The parent's fidelity AC ('no fidelity regression vs the current per-child behavior') is at risk for the first batching child in the DAG.\"\n  checklist_item: \"Check the 7 cross-child modes — scope overlap / conflicting assumptions (the per-child guardrail S4 depends on is owned by a later sibling and absent from S4).\"\n  suggested_fix: \"Add to S4's '## What' and AC a REQUIRED structured per-child/per-bin output guarantee (each child id in the bin returns a finding list OR an explicit 'clean' marker), mirroring S5's guardrail, so the merged call cannot silently omit a tail child; and have S4's declared S6 fidelity gate explicitly check TAIL-child recall, per the shared meta-comment. Alternatively, pull S5's guardrail forward into S4, or make S4's fidelity AC depend on S5's guardrail landing first.\""},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782578826629387001,"uuid":"b0ac5831-cead-4ba0-8c26-f2cd9147bdce"}